text:
"I use all my reaction storage but very little of my cast storage. Can storage units be flexible?"

> Flexible storage units are very tricky to implement with a good UX. There are many problems, but the most pressing one is what to do when you’ve exceeded the limit and send a new message. The only solution with our eventually consistent network is to prune the oldest message, irrespective of type. This means that if you run out of space and like something, the first person you followed may get unfollowed, which is really bad. There is no easy solution to this problem.

cast.text:
1/2 A few composer action ideas

1. Gated polls based on criteria — you can only vote if...
    a. Onchain activity — age of wallet, token balance, holding an NFT
    b. Farcaster activity — age of account, # of followers, OpenRank or Power Badge

2. Remind me — useful for live virtual events like Farhouse, Unlonely, /tabletop game night; creates a frame with a single button to remind the user via a programmatic DC 1 hour or 15 minutes before event is live

3. Waitlist — useful for building excitement about a consumer app launch; creates a frame with single button to join the wailist; admin UI is a table of FIDs and relevant metrics, ability to invite users to the app via a programmatic DC

4. Prop bet — creates a frame with a description, $ amount, odds and resolver (i.e. 3rd party who decides who won the bet) for a prop bet against the caster. Transaction on Base in USDC? Degen?

I truly realized I was in my 40s when I brushed my teeth with itch cream
I don't know what Chocolate Rain is and at this point i'm too afraid to ask
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EwTZ2xpQwpA

The 3 years I was in law school was like a black hole. SO many cultural phenomenons happened that I was completely unaware of in my little legal bubble. 

I love discovering them randomly every now and then. Like today, when @tayzonday kept popping up on my feed. 

Had no clue who he was, but lots of folks were engaging so I did some google snooping and it turns out he had an insanely viral song that currently has 138 million views on YouTube.

But it came out in 2007 during my law school haze. So I never even heard of it. 

Now he's on Farcaster and I get to play catch up, so welcome to the purple app Tay! Aloha 🤙

Chocolate Rain is a popular internet video and song that gained widespread attention in the mid-2000s. It was created by musician and internet personality Tay Zonday, and features his deep, distinctive voice singing about social issues over a catchy, repetitive melody. The song's lyrics and music video address themes of racism and discrimination, and it quickly became a viral sensation, receiving millions of views on YouTube. Despite its somewhat unusual subject matter, Chocolate Rain has endured as a memorable piece of internet culture and remains a popular meme to this day.
